# Load necessary libraries
library(randomForest)
## Warning: package 'randomForest' was built under R version 4.3.2
## randomForest 4.7-1.1
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     combine
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     margin
library(rpart)
## Warning: package 'rpart' was built under R version 4.3.3
library(rpart.plot)
## Warning: package 'rpart.plot' was built under R version 4.3.3
library(ggplot2)
# Convert 'TOTAL' from character to numeric after removing commas
data$TOTAL <- as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data$TOTAL))

# Check for NAs which might have been introduced by coercion
sum(is.na(data$TOTAL))
## [1] 0
# 'TOTAL' is likely our target variable, and 'S No' is just an identifier
model_data <- data[, -c(1, ncol(data))]

# Set up the target variable
target <- data$TOTAL

# Build the Random Forest model
rf_model <- randomForest(x = model_data, y = target, ntree = 100)

# Plot variable importance
varImpPlot(rf_model)

# Build the Decision Tree model
dt_model <- rpart(TOTAL ~ ., data = data[, -1]) # exclude 'S No' for modeling

# Plot the decision tree
rpart.plot(dt_model)

# Generate predictions from both models (example for the training data itself)
rf_predictions <- predict(rf_model, model_data)
dt_predictions <- predict(dt_model, model_data)

# Plot predictions vs. actual values
# For Random Forest
rf_pred_actual <- data.frame(Actual = target, Predicted = rf_predictions)
ggplot(rf_pred_actual, aes(x = Actual, y = Predicted)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "blue") +
  ggtitle("Random Forest: Actual vs Predicted")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# For Decision Tree
dt_pred_actual <- data.frame(Actual = target, Predicted = dt_predictions)
ggplot(dt_pred_actual, aes(x = Actual, y = Predicted)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") +
  ggtitle("Decision Tree: Actual vs Predicted")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

#Metrics for Descision Tree and Random Forest
# Load necessary library
library(Metrics)
## Warning: package 'Metrics' was built under R version 4.3.3
library(caret)
## Warning: package 'caret' was built under R version 4.3.2
## Loading required package: lattice
## 
## Attaching package: 'caret'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:Metrics':
## 
##     precision, recall
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     lift
data$TOTAL <- as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data$TOTAL))
data <- na.omit(data)  # Remove rows with NAs, especially in the 'TOTAL' column

# Calculate MAE and RMSE for Random Forest predictions
rf_mae <- mae(data$TOTAL, rf_predictions)
rf_rmse <- rmse(data$TOTAL, rf_predictions)
rf_me <- mean(data$TOTAL - rf_predictions)  # Calculate Mean Error for Random Forest

# Calculate MAE and RMSE for Decision Tree predictions
dt_mae <- mae(data$TOTAL, dt_predictions)
dt_rmse <- rmse(data$TOTAL, dt_predictions)
dt_me <- mean(data$TOTAL - dt_predictions)  # Calculate Mean Error for Decision Tree

# Calculate additional metrics for Random Forest predictions
rf_mse <- mse(data$TOTAL, rf_predictions)
rf_mape <- mape(data$TOTAL, rf_predictions)
rf_msle <- msle(data$TOTAL, rf_predictions)

# Calculate additional metrics for Decision Tree predictions
dt_mse <- mse(data$TOTAL, dt_predictions)
dt_mape <- mape(data$TOTAL, dt_predictions)
dt_msle <- msle(data$TOTAL, dt_predictions)

# Calculate MASE for both models
# First, compute a naïve forecast which uses the previous value to predict the next one
naive_forecast <- c(NA, data$TOTAL[-length(data$TOTAL)])
naive_mae <- mae(data$TOTAL[-1], naive_forecast[-1])  # Exclude the first NA value
naive_me <- mean(data$TOTAL[-1] - naive_forecast[-1])  # Calculate Mean Error for naive forecast

rf_mase <- rf_mae / naive_mae
dt_mase <- dt_mae / naive_mae

rf_mes <- rf_me / naive_me  # Calculate Mean Error Scaled for Random Forest
dt_mes <- dt_me / naive_me  # Calculate Mean Error Scaled for Decision Tree

# Print the metrics
cat("Metrics for Random Forest Model:\n")
## Metrics for Random Forest Model:
cat("ME:", rf_me, "\n")
## ME: 3243.613
cat("MAE:", rf_mae, "\n")
## MAE: 7438.206
cat("RMSE:", rf_rmse, "\n")
## RMSE: 194781.3
cat("MSE:", rf_mse, "\n")
## MSE: 37939765534
cat("MAPE:", rf_mape, "\n")
## MAPE: 5.233705
cat("MSLE:", rf_msle, "\n")
## MSLE: 1.522616
cat("MASE:", rf_mase, "\n")
## MASE: 0.07539535
cat("MES:", rf_mes, "\n\n")
## MES: -6574.386
cat("Metrics for Decision Tree Model:\n")
## Metrics for Decision Tree Model:
cat("ME:", dt_me, "\n")
## ME: 1.989667e-13
cat("MAE:", dt_mae, "\n")
## MAE: 33813.98
cat("RMSE:", dt_rmse, "\n")
## RMSE: 476420
cat("MSE:", dt_mse, "\n")
## MSE: 2.26976e+11
cat("MAPE:", dt_mape, "\n")
## MAPE: 830.72
cat("MSLE:", dt_msle, "\n")
## MSLE: 25.91248
cat("MASE:", dt_mase, "\n")
## MASE: 0.3427462
cat("MES:", dt_mes, "\n")
## MES: -4.032799e-13
# R-squared for Random Forest
rf_r2 <- R2(rf_predictions, data$TOTAL)
cat("R-squared for Random Forest:", rf_r2, "\n")
## R-squared for Random Forest: 0.9608843
# R-squared for Decision Tree
dt_r2 <- R2(dt_predictions, data$TOTAL)

# Read the CSV file
library(readxl)
sales_data <- read_excel("C:/Users/chenc/OneDrive/Desktop/yearwise-sales-dataof maker for past 5 years.xlsx")

# Check the data
yearly_sales <- sales_data[,2:6]  # Adjust the column indices if necessary

# Aggregate the sales data by year
total_sales_by_year <- colSums(yearly_sales, na.rm = TRUE)

# Convert the aggregated data to a time series object
ts_data <- ts(total_sales_by_year, start = 2019, frequency = 1)

# Fit an ARIMA model
fit_arima <- auto.arima(ts_data)
summary(fit_arima)
## Series: ts_data 
## ARIMA(0,0,0) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           mean
##       21446200
## s.e.   1062601
## 
## sigma^2 = 7.055e+12:  log likelihood = -80.5
## AIC=165   AICc=171   BIC=164.22
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                        ME    RMSE     MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE
## Training set 5.960555e-09 2375779 2146441 -1.252221 10.19258 0.7881731
##                     ACF1
## Training set -0.01542212
# Forecast future sales
future_sales_arima <- forecast(fit_arima, h = 2)  # Forecast for 2 additional years
plot(future_sales_arima)

#ARIMA Model

library(forecast)  # for forecast and accuracy functions

# Assuming ts_data is your complete time series data
# Split the data into training and test sets
# Select all but the last data point for training
training_data <- ts_data[1:(length(ts_data)-1)]
# Select only the last data point for testing
test_data <- ts_data[length(ts_data)]

# Fit an ARIMA model on the training set
fit_arima <- auto.arima(training_data)
summary(fit_arima)
## Series: training_data 
## ARIMA(0,0,0) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           mean
##       20772002
## s.e.   1093537
## 
## sigma^2 = 6.377e+12:  log likelihood = -64.07
## AIC=132.14   AICc=144.14   BIC=130.91
## 
## Training set error measures:
##              ME    RMSE     MAE       MPE     MAPE     MASE      ACF1
## Training set  0 2186938 2008854 -1.077132 9.635474 1.121695 0.2661827
# Forecast the next period (which is our test set)
forecasted_values <- forecast(fit_arima, h = 1)

# Assuming that the forecast and the actual data for the test period are now aligned
accuracy_metrics <- accuracy(forecasted_values, test_data)

# Print the accuracy metrics
print(accuracy_metrics)
##                   ME    RMSE     MAE       MPE      MAPE     MASE      ACF1
## Training set       0 2186938 2008854 -1.077132  9.635474 1.121695 0.2661827
## Test set     3370987 3370987 3370987 13.962591 13.962591 1.882277        NA
# If you want to display specific metrics
cat("Mean Error (ME):", accuracy_metrics[1, "ME"], "\n")
## Mean Error (ME): 0
cat("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "MAE"], "\n")
## Mean Absolute Error (MAE): 2008854
cat("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "RMSE"], "\n")
## Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): 2186938
cat("Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "MAPE"], "\n")
## Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE): 9.635474
cat("Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "MASE"], "\n")
## Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE): 1.121695

#Exponential Smoothing
# Load the necessary library
library(forecast)

# Assuming ts_data is your complete time series data
# Split the data into training and test sets
training_data <- ts_data[1:(length(ts_data)-2)]
test_data <- ts_data[(length(ts_data)-1):length(ts_data)]

# Fit an ETS model on the training set
ets_model <- ets(training_data)
summary(ets_model)
## ETS(A,A,N) 
## 
## Call:
##  ets(y = training_data) 
## 
##   Smoothing parameters:
##     alpha = 1 
##     beta  = 0 
## 
##   Initial states:
##     l = 23995195 
##     b = -2428677 
## 
##   sigma:  1408691
## Training set error measures:
##                    ME    RMSE      MAE    MPE     MAPE      MASE       ACF1
## Training set 731554.7 1408691 887563.3 2.9612 3.786476 0.3486542 -0.1230927
# Forecast the next 2 periods (which are our test set)
ets_forecast <- forecast(ets_model, h = 2)

# Plot the forecast
plot(ets_forecast)

# Print the forecasted values
print(ets_forecast)
##   Point Forecast    Lo 80    Hi 80    Lo 95    Hi 95
## 4       16475151 14669840 18280462 13714167 19236135
## 5       14046474 11493379 16599569 10141853 17951095
# Calculate accuracy metrics
accuracy_metrics <- accuracy(ets_forecast, test_data)
print(accuracy_metrics)
##                     ME    RMSE       MAE      MPE      MAPE      MASE
## Training set  731554.7 1408691  887563.3  2.96120  3.786476 0.3486542
## Test set     6121916.0 7298993 6121916.0 26.67522 26.675221 2.4048221
##                    ACF1
## Training set -0.1230927
## Test set             NA
# Calculate R-squared manually
observations <- test_data  # Actual observed values
predictions <- ets_forecast$mean  # Predicted values from ETS

SSE <- sum((observations - predictions)^2)
SST <- sum((observations - mean(observations))^2)
R_squared <- 1 - (SSE/SST)

# Print the metrics including R-squared
cat("Mean Error (ME):", accuracy_metrics[1, "ME"], "\n")
## Mean Error (ME): 731554.7
cat("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "MAE"], "\n")
## Mean Absolute Error (MAE): 887563.3
cat("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "RMSE"], "\n")
## Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): 1408691
mse_value <- accuracy_metrics[1, "RMSE"]^2
cat("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", mse_value, "\n")
## Mean Squared Error (MSE): 1.984411e+12
cat("Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "MAPE"], "\n")
## Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE): 3.786476
cat("Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):", accuracy_metrics[1, "MASE"], "\n")
## Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE): 0.3486542
cat("R-squared:", R_squared, "\n")
## R-squared: -5.992391

# Adjust model parameters for regularization
library(xgboost)
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(readxl)

# Load data
data <- read_excel("C:/Users/chenc/OneDrive/Desktop/yearwise-sales-dataof maker for past 5 years.xlsx")

# Ensure character data is converted to numeric where applicable
data <- data %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), as.numeric))
## Warning: There was 1 warning in `mutate()`.
## ℹ In argument: `across(where(is.character), as.numeric)`.
## Caused by warning:
## ! NAs introduced by coercion
# Split the data into predictors (X) and target (y)
X <- subset(data, select = -TOTAL)
y <- data$TOTAL

# Build the XGBoost model
set.seed(42)
xgb_model <- xgboost(data = as.matrix(X), label = y, nrounds = 500, max_depth = 1, eta = 0.1, lambda = 3, alpha = 1, objective = "reg:squarederror", nfold = 6)

# Get predicted values on the training data
predicted <- predict(xgb_model, as.matrix(X))

# Visualize actual vs predicted
plot(y, predicted, xlab = "Actual", ylab = "Predicted", main = "Actual vs Predicted")
abline(0, 1, col = "red")  # Add a 45-degree line for reference

# Calculate and print the model performance metrics
mse <- mean((predicted - y)^2)  # Mean Squared Error
rmse <- sqrt(mse)  # Root Mean Squared Error
me <- mean(predicted - y)  # Mean Error
mae <- mean(abs(predicted - y))  # Mean Absolute Error
mape <- mean(abs((y - predicted) / y)) * 100  # Mean Absolute Percentage Error

# Calculate R-squared
SS_Residual <- sum((y - predicted)^2)
SS_Total <- sum((y - mean(y))^2)
rsquared <- 1 - (SS_Residual / SS_Total)

# Calculate MASE
naive_forecast <- c(NA, y[-length(y)])
naive_mae <- mean(abs(y[-1] - naive_forecast[-1]))
mase <- mae / naive_mae

# Print all metrics
cat("Mean Error (ME):", me, "\n")
## Mean Error (ME): 0.0364434
cat("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", mae, "\n")
## Mean Absolute Error (MAE): 863.439
cat("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", rmse, "\n")
## Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): 4905.057
cat("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", mse, "\n")
## Mean Squared Error (MSE): 24059581
cat("Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE):", mape, "%\n")
## Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE): 4791.128 %
cat("Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE):", mase, "\n")
## Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE): 0.008752015
cat("R-squared:", rsquared, "\n")
## R-squared: 0.9999654
# Feature importance
importance_matrix <- xgb.importance(feature_names = colnames(X), model = xgb_model)
xgb.plot.importance(importance_matrix)

# Make sure all libraries are loaded
library(randomForest)
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(readxl)

# Load data
data <- read_excel("C:/Users/chenc/OneDrive/Desktop/yearwise-sales-dataof maker for past 5 years.xlsx")

 

# Split the data into predictors (X) and target (y)
X <- subset(data, select = -TOTAL)
y <- data$TOTAL

# Build the Random Forest model
# Build the Random Forest model with adjusted hyperparameters
set.seed(42)
rf_model <- randomForest(x = X, y = y, ntree = 1000, mtry = 3, max_depth = 20)

# Print the model
print(rf_model)
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(x = X, y = y, ntree = 1000, mtry = 3, max_depth = 20) 
##                Type of random forest: regression
##                      Number of trees: 1000
## No. of variables tried at each split: 3
## 
##           Mean of squared residuals: 104984847520
##                     % Var explained: 84.92
# Get predicted values on the training data
predicted <- predict(rf_model, X)

# Calculate Mean Squared Error (MSE)
mse <- mean((predicted - y)^2)

# Calculate R-squared
rsquared <- cor(predicted, y)^2

# Print MSE and R-squared
cat("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", mse, "\n")
## Mean Squared Error (MSE): 37218055126
cat("R-squared:", rsquared, "\n")
## R-squared: 0.9598799

# Plot the data


# Load the necessary libraries
library(shiny)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)




# Define the user interface
ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Maker Sales Dashboard"),
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      selectInput("maker", "Choose a Maker:", choices = unique(clean_data$Maker)),
      selectInput("year", "Choose a Year:", choices = c("2019", "2020", "2021", "2022", "2023"))
    ),
    mainPanel(
      textOutput("salesInfo"),
      plotOutput("salesBarPlot"),
      plotOutput("salesPieChart")
    )
  )
)

# Define the server logic
server <- function(input, output) {
  output$salesInfo <- renderText({
    selected_maker <- input$maker
    selected_year <- input$year
    sales_data <- clean_data %>%
      filter(Maker == selected_maker) %>%
      select(selected_year, TOTAL) %>%
      drop_na()
    
    paste("Total sales for", selected_maker, "in", selected_year, "is:", sales_data[[1]], "\n",
          "Cumulative sales from 2019 to", selected_year, "is:", sales_data[[2]])
  })
  
  output$salesBarPlot <- renderPlot({
    selected_maker <- input$maker
    sales_data <- clean_data %>%
      filter(Maker == selected_maker) %>%
      select(`2019`, `2020`, `2021`, `2022`, `2023`) %>%
      pivot_longer(cols = c(`2019`, `2020`, `2021`, `2022`, `2023`), names_to = "Year", values_to = "Sales")
    
    ggplot(sales_data, aes(x = Year, y = Sales, fill = Year)) +
      geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
      labs(title = paste("Total Sales for", selected_maker, "by Year"), x = "Year", y = "Sales") +
      theme_minimal()
  })
  
  output$salesPieChart <- renderPlot({
    selected_maker <- input$maker
    sales_data <- clean_data %>%
      filter(Maker == selected_maker) %>%
      select(`2019`, `2020`, `2021`, `2022`, `2023`) %>%
      pivot_longer(cols = c(`2019`, `2020`, `2021`, `2022`, `2023`), names_to = "Year", values_to = "Sales")
    
    ggplot(sales_data, aes(x = "", y = Sales, fill = Year)) +
      geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity") +
      coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
      theme_void() +
      labs(fill = "Year") +
      theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
      labs(title = paste("Sales Distribution for", selected_maker))
  })
}

# Run the application
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)
